			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2011</a> paper:</span><br><i>Reusing Pattern Solutions in Modeling: A Generic Approach Based on a Role Language</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/ChristopheTombelle.html">Christophe Tombelle</a>, <a href="../profile/GillesVanwormhoudt.html">Gilles Vanwormhoudt</a>, <a href="../profile/EmmanuelRenaux.html">Emmanuel Renaux</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-28830-2_8">10.1007/978-3-642-28830-2_8</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1e.html"><span class="tagM">T1E: Reuse</span></a><ul><li> The paper explicitly targets reuse by capturing design pattern solutions in a generic role-based form.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagL">T3C: DSLs</span></a><ul><li> The ‘role language’ is a domain-specific notation for expressing reusable pattern structures.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1a.html"><span class="tagL">T1A: Design</span></a><ul><li> Defining a role language entails language design choices to represent patterns uniformly.
</li></ul></li></ul>
